cLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.Group\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.Group\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.Group\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.Group\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.Normed.Field.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Measure.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.Group\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.Measure\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.Group\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits.SpecificLimits",
      "\n  rw [h1]",
      "Solving the Algebra Problem in Lean 4\n\nWe need to prove that for a finite-dimensional central simple algebra $B$ over a number field $K$, and for any unit $u$ in $B \\otimes K$, the left and right multiplication by $u$ have the same effect on the additive Haar measure.\n\nFirst, let's think about the structure of the problem. We have:\n- A number field $K$\n- A finite-dimensional central simple algebra $B$ over $K$\n- A unit $u \\in B \\otimes K$\n- We need to show that multiplying by $u$ on the left and right preserves the additive Haar measure\n\nIn measure theory, two transformations have the same effect on a measure if they are equal as maps. So we need to show that the left multiplication by $u$ and the right multiplication by $u$ are the same transformation on the additive group $B \\otimes K$.\n\nFor a unit $u \\in B \\otimes K$, the left multiplication is $L_u(x) = u \\cdot x$ and the right multiplication is $R_u(x) = x \\cdot u$. We need to show $L_u = R_u$ as transformations.\n\nBut in the ring $B \\otimes K$, since $B$ is central, the multiplication from $B$ and $K$ commute. Therefore, for any $b \\in B$ and $k \\in K$, we have $b \\cdot k = k \\cdot b$. Therefore, in the ring $B \\otimes K$, left and right multiplication commute with the center. But since the center is $K$, and the multiplication from $K$ is central, left and right multiplication must be the same.\n\nTherefore, $L_u = R_u$, so they have the same effect on the measure.\n\nNow, let's translate this into Lean 4. The goal is to show that for a unit $u \\in B \\otimes K$, the left and right multiplications have the same effect on the additive Haar measure.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Algebra.Central.Basic\n/-!\n\n# Solving the Algebra Problem in Lean 4\n\nWe need to prove that for a finite-dimensional central simple algebra $B$ over a number field $K$, and for any unit $u \\in B \\otimes K$, the left and right multiplication by $u$ have the same effect on the additive Haar measure.